Source: The Toronto Star 29 Aug 2000, 01:41 EDT [edited

Plum pox potyvirus detected near Chatham, ON; origin a mystery
----------------------------------------------------------------
HAMILTON - Canadian officials are rethinking their theory that the plum pox
virus came to Canada solely from Pennsylvania. Blake Ferguson of the
Canadian Food Inspection Agency confirmed yesterday that the virus has been
found in peach trees at Blenheim, on the north shore of Lake Erie near
Chatham. None of the trees came from the United States.
It's the first time the virus has been found outside Niagara, said
Ferguson, who is helping co-ordinate the agency's national strategy for
identification and eradication. "It points to the fact it's been around
longer than we had originally assumed. It may not have arrived from
Pennsylvania." As of yesterday there have been 510 positive tests for the D
strain of the virus, out of 37 412 samples.
Officials are concerned that an infected tree might have been smuggled into
Canada. But how the virus got to Blenheim is a mystery. Ferguson said
Canada's records are very good on imported plants, making tracking of legal
stock simple. But a plant smuggled from outside Canada cannot be traced.
Ferguson also said it's possible the disease, originally from Europe, has
been here longer than we know. It may have been undetected for some time on
a non-farm operation, where owners were not concerned about the quality of
fruit.
Ferguson said it's probable that some varieties of fruit trees will be less
likely to get the disease, and some will be more susceptible. Future work
will look at breeding trees that are highly resistant to the virus. U.S.
researchers already have developed resistant strains through genetic
alteration and are testing them in Europe where the disease originated.
--
