[If true, then this is a major setback in managing this disease. I am not
surprised that the virus may have already been in Canada for a period of
time. I once saw a tourist at Schipol Airport stuffing plantlets into
plastic bags which he then put into his pockets. Upon my telling him that
he would likely be interrogated by USDA officials at New York, he mumbled
something about "mind your own business!"
Plum pox potyvirus was initially discovered in nectarines imported into
Canada from a nursery in Pennsylvania two years ago but subsequent tests of
that nursery by American scientists failed to detect the virus. It is
likely that the infected trees were shipped out in the normal course of
commerce before the survey was made. -Mod.DH
